**Privacy Policy — Volume Booster**

Last updated: April 2026

This Privacy Policy explains how **Volume Booster** handles your data. It is available as a Chrome extension and as a Safari Web Extension for macOS and iOS. Developed by Victor Humenhuk.

**In short**

- No data leaves your device.
- No tracking, no analytics, no ads.
- Nothing is saved to disk, not even your volume settings.

**What the Extension does**

Volume Booster uses the Web Audio API to amplify video and audio on the page you're viewing, beyond the normal 100% limit. All processing happens locally in your browser.

**What it collects**

Nothing. The Extension does not collect, store, transmit, or share:

- Personal information (name, email, identifiers)
- Browsing history or web activity
- Authentication or financial information
- Location data
- Website content
- Analytics or telemetry

**Data storage**

None persisted. Volume settings live in memory only and reset when you close or refresh the page.

**Data sharing**

None. The Extension makes no external network requests and talks to no servers. No data is sold, transferred, or disclosed to any third party.

**Third-party services**

None. No analytics, advertising, or tracking of any kind.

**Permissions**

**Chrome**

- Host access (`<all_urls>`): inject a content script that detects and boosts media on the active page. Not used to read, collect, or transmit page content.

**Safari (macOS and iOS)**

- Website access (all websites): same purpose as above. Safari requires you to grant this, and you can revoke or limit it to specific sites at any time in Safari settings.

**Apple privacy**

On iOS and macOS, the Extension runs inside Apple's App Sandbox and WebExtensions security model. It does not access other apps, the clipboard, camera, microphone, location, contacts, or any other protected resource. No App Tracking Transparency disclosure is needed because no tracking occurs.

**Children's privacy**

The Extension does not knowingly collect data from anyone, including children under 13.

